<Author>stez867
<Content>Nice hotel  My husband  I stayed at the Hotel de Las Letras in April 2008 for 2 nights. The hotel is very close to at least 3 metro stops-sol/sevilla/gran via. when coming from the airport you can get off at any one of these and have only a 5 minute walk-very easy.the hotel is on the corner of gran via, and the entrance doesn't look like a hotel entrance-it looks like an apartment entrance. and when you go in you are even more oncfused because there are no signs inside the door about the ohtel. but we just waited (very long time to check in even though there was only 2 people in front of me, not sure why it takes so long) and found out we were in the right place.The room was lovely-great bedding, very modern decor, nice bathroom with large tub and all the toiletries you could need. a large safe that fit our laptop  lladro purchases. both streets the hotel is on are noisy, i had to use earplugs my first night even though we were on the 'quieter' street, but i would still reocmmend it. we found a tapas bar one block away where we had 4 tapas  2 beers for 7 euros-can't beat that! the front desk was not very friendly, and you are best to speak in spanish everywhere you go in spain (easy for us as i speak spanish), so would encourage you to do some reading  learn key phrases before you go. i don't pick a hotel for the friendly front desk so that does not bother me. as long as the room is comfortable and of quality to the price paid, and everything is clean i don't care about attitudes. madrid is not english friendly, and even the royal palace (palacio real) does not have enlish translations on the signs in the armory. and we ran into another american tourist and they told us they had trouble eating because many restaurants did not have english menus. we found a lot that did and if you stay on main streets you will be fine (albeit won't experience as much of the culture if you stick to tourist restaurants).note the hotel is not handicap accessible-you have to walk up 4-5 steps to enter the hotel. most of madrid isn't accessible, but it is better than barcelona where we had to carry our luggage up mutliple flights in the metros-madrid has more escalators in the metros.all in all, we loved madrid, the hotel was great, and would recommend it to anyone. 
