<Content>Trendy  I was in Madrid on business and wanted to stay one day longer to explore the city. I mainly chose this hotel based on its location and the fitness  spa facilities, as I wanted to treat myself to some pampering after the working week. When I arrived at the hotel on Friday afternoon, I was told that both the fitness room and the spa were closed. Naturally I was very disappointed and told them that this should have been mentioned on their website. After some complaining and begging they did eventually let me into the gym, but that was also a letdown as it consisted of one treadmill and one exercise bike. I suppose the Spanish idea of a gym is different from the English one. As I couldn't break into a sweat with the malfunctioning equipment, I eventually ended up going for a jog in the nearby Parque del Retiro in +28 C heat. It surely did the job.After a bad start I wasn't particularly impressed with the trendy room that had been furnished with Ikea-like furniture. I found it cheap and lacking in character, but that is just my personal opinion. The biblioteca downstairs looked nice though, but the restaurant I found a bit too dark. The hotel has a very good location as it is a walking distance from restaurants and shops. All in all, it wasn't too bad, but next time I will try something else. 
