<Author>schippk
<Content>Sophisticated and comfortable Whenever I book a stylish hipster hotel Iike the de las Letras I worry that when the front desk sees a middle-aged couple not wearing Versace and lugging old suitcases through the lobby our reservation will suddenly be misplaced. Not to worry at this hotel. My husband and I arrived utterly exhausted and miserable after sprinting through Heathrow to catch our connection to Madrid. We discovered upon arrival that the above-mentioned old suitcases, being checked and therefore unable to sprint with us, were still in London. The front desk staff at the de las Letras listed patiently to my bad Spanish and responded politely in perfect English that our room was ready.The room was even better than it had looked on the hotel's website. Despite our less-than-glamorous appearance, my husband and I are interested in modern design and look forward to opportunities to see what's new and cutting-edge. In this the hotel did not disappoint. The sliding door to the bathroom was a solid piece of cobalt blue lucite. We had a flat-screen TV with a full range of satellite channels, including CNN and the BBC. The walls were a beautiful paprika color. The immaculate and surprisingly large bathroom was fully stocked with toiletries, including disposable razors. In addition to the usual what's going on in Madrid this week magazines, the room had a pocket design guide to the city showing where all the most stylish restaurants and shopping were to be found. The platform bed was comfortable, and everything was spotless. The room was small, but not unduly so considering the hotel is in an old building. The elevators were also quite small, but again no more so than is typical in Europe.The only thing we found strange was the lights: We initially thought that none were working, but discovered that you needed to slide the room's key card into a holder near the door to enable the electricity. We later learned this energy-saving feature (you can't leave the room with the lights on) was common in Spain.The hotel has a restaurant, but we did not eat there as the neighborhood is full of places to eat. I did use the library, as it has several Internet-connected computers set up for guests. I sent an e-mail to my family at home. Oddly, they received it two weeks later. I suspect the message was delayed at Heathrow.We never heard the slightest noise from any of the other rooms. The weather was unseasonably cold so we had the windows closed most of the time. However when we did open the French doors to our tiny (barely room to stand) balcony, there was plenty of noise from the bustling street below.The hotel's location is absolutely superb. It is on a main boulevard full of shops and restaurants. If you venture off to the side a few blocks behind the hotel you will come across what we called Hooker Street, but even that slightly seedy area wasn't that alarming compared to, say, the Tenderloin in San Francisco. The area immediately surrounding the hotel is fine. We took the roughly five-block walk to the Prado the day after we arrived. I advise against going to see Goya's Black Paintings and Heironymous Bosch's Garden of Earthly Delights when you have severe jet lag. Luckily for my frame of mind, we got back to the hotel just as the bellhops were carrying our luggage, delivered by the airline, up to our room. One thing happened while we were at the de las Letras that might have bothered some people: On our second night there, we discovered that a film set had been assembled in the street immediately below our room. A bank of klieg lights mounted on a crane was directly outside our window. We were fascinated by the milling scene of technicians and directors below us, (I kept peering out hoping to see Pedro Almodovar or Penelope Cruz) but having a movie filmed outside your hotel room is not everyone's cup of cafe con leche. There was almost no noise from the film set except briefly in the middle of the night, when my husband heard a sound and was lucky enough to make it to the balcony in time so see some sort of police chase scene being filmed. The klieg lights, however, shone brightly into our room all night. We had heavy drapes which helped, but I was glad I had an eye mask (never travel without one).At 118 Euros per night we thought this place was a spectaculary good value, especially since it is a designer hotel. Breakfast, as in most places in southern Europe, was not included and was an additional 7 Euros (about US$10 at the wretched exchange rate that was current during our trip) per person. Instead, we just went to one of the local cafes a couple of blocks from the hotel each morning and had coffee and the donunt-like churros (along with the equivalent of a couple of cigarettes seondhand as everybody smokes like fiends in Spain, including in restaurants) for about 2 Euros each.We absolutely loved this hotel and would go back in a hot minute. 
