<Author>Solario
<Content>Excellent Location, My wife and I (50 years old) spent a weekend at Las Letras Hotel.We found the staff at the reception exceptionally professional, friendly and courtious. The outside of the building is beautifully sculpted and well restored. We stayed in a regular room and did not upgrade to a room with a jacuzzi, nor to one with a balcony.The hotel is located directly on Gran Via which is one of the busiest streets in Madrid and we saw no use of stepping out onto a balcony to watch the trafic jam and smell the exhaust fumes. A whirlpool in the basement can be used free of charge by hotel guests so bring a bathing suit. The water however was warm at best. There is also one treadmill and an excercise bike in a room that's a bit gloomy with a low ceiling. The Spa staff was very friendly and helpful. The rooms are in a modern design style. We found it to be very clean, functional. The room's designer lights are meant to create an atmosphere, not to read by so don't expect to finish your novel there. Reception on English language TV stations was not great but Spanish TV was perfect. Our first night (Friday) was very restful. On Saturday night there was a private party in a reception room and I heard the thumping of the techno beat all night long which managed to rattle my skull even though I tried sleeping with earplugs on. Doors slammed all night long as party-goers came and went into the Madrid Movida. You might request a high floor to avoid the party noise. We did not try the restaurant which did good business but was a bit too trendy for us old folks. The location is terrific - a 15 minute walk from the Prado, 5 minutes to Sol. I would recommend this hotel especially if you wish to spend a weekend is a great location, benefit from friendly staff and contemplate poetry written on the walls. 
