<Author>Leeds_Visitor
<Content>Average standard, poor service and Beware of Theft scam in Madrid We stayed in this hotel between 19th and 20th January 2007 for the short weekend break in Madrid. It is about 15 miles away from the Barajas airport, costing us 30 euros on Taxi fare to get there, no stopping space outside. When we stopped, there was a bus right on the back side of the Taxi, the Taxi driver protested to the bus driver and had to squeeze in to get our luggage. It is on a very busy main street. The entrance is small and not very prominent; the reception area is tiny and not at all impressive although the receptionist was efficient with a good understanding of English, the checking in was without any problem. We had a double room on the 5th floor, the lift was dark with very dim blue light. The room was very dark with red wall and little lighting just as other Trip Adviser members had previously described. Room was very average with two single beds pushed together to make up a double bed although we asked for a double bed. The beds were comfortable with light quilts and good pillows. We asked for a quiet room and were put in a room at the back without any view to the streets and could hardly see any day light, but it was reasonably quiet. The room was too warm and the air conditioning was very noisy, you just could not leave the air conditioning on to have a good night sleep. We arrived late on Friday, and decided to eat in the Hotel rather than venture out into town. The restaurant is right next to the Lounge where people smoke; as a non-smoker, it was very uncomfortable. The menu was very limited and pricy, the portions were extremely tiny, both my wife and I are light eaters, but we were just astonished as how little we got and still felt very hungry on our first night. You get exactly what you asked for without any dressing or anything else with it, we had to order side orders, even the sauce is extra. I do not recommended the hotel restaurant at all, the service were extremely poor. The breakfast was very average with very limited choice for 14 euros each, again you are better off eating out. The hotel was clean but the room facilities were average for a 4 star hotel, no tea/coffee making facility either. The only positive side of this hotel is the location, very central in Madrid with easy access to the major attraction and a short uphill walk to the Gran Via Metro. In summary, I do not recommend this hotel, and give it 2.5 out of 5. We travel around 6 times a year and I still favour the American chain hotels such as Hilton, Marriott and Sheraton where they have so far kept up with their high standards.Getting around in central Madrid was easy with a two-day Metro tourist travel pass that also allow you to travel to the airport, costing both of us just less than 14 euros. We used the Metro on the way back to the airport, but if you have a lot of luggage, I would recommend a Taxi; there were a lot of steps going up and down with two line changes and no seat at busy time. We also went on the Madrid Vision tour bus, but very disappointed with it. We had to wait for a long time for the bus to arrive, at many stopping points; people queued for a long time just to be told that they could not get on because there was not enough space on the bus. There were too few buses running.Beware of Madrid hustlers and theft scam!I was tricked in Madrid and lost 140 Euros as a result. I was approached by a Middle Eastern looking man dressed as a tourist with camera hanging at the front and a map pretending to ask me for direction and made friend with me. He then showed me a foreign note and said he was interested in seeing a small nomination Pound note. I was stupid enough to do as he said and took my wallet out, as soon as he saw my euros, he then quickly took all my euros out from my wallet and said wanting to feel the watermark on these notes and asked me some stupid questions at the same time about the exchange rate to distract me. He kept rubbing these notes and at the same time secretly took 7 of my 20Euro notes without me knowing. He then put my notes back into my wallet and left, as soon as I turned around his accomplice holding a map came over to ask me to show him where he was on the map to distract me from checking my wallet. By the time I realised the scam, and checked my wallet, 7 out of my 10 20-euro notes had gone and the tricksters were long gone. I just could not believe I could be so stupid and foolish to fall into this trap. Perhaps I was over-friendly and being too helpful. This is a very hard lesson to learn and be very careful in Madrid, NEVER NEVER show your wallet to a stranger. And walk away if you are approached by strangers, I would rather be rude than suffering losses again. This had really ruined our holiday.In comparison, we preferred Barcelona than Madrid, Barcelona has more in character, and more tourist attractions which suited us much better, Madrid is just another capital city. 
