<Content>We liked it! We stayed 4 nights in Standard room. It had 2 seater sofa for resting Prado weary feet. As others say the rooms have dim lights and dark walls but the bathroom was fine. Strangely the lift is very dark with only violet lights! The corridors are very light and airy, much better than most hotels, so i guess it is all down to personal taste.The bar area is very good for coffee and snacks as well as drinks and seems very popular with locals. Try the tart Tatin with ice cream. As ever though it is VERY dark. No chance of reading the books that are used as decor. We went down to the nice library when we wanted to get some peace and quiet.The restaurant is a strange mix of Japan meets Heston Blumenthal, since a main course can be had for about 拢10(12 euro) and wine is 2.50E a glass it is great value and well worth a try.Back to the room, the bathroom has two sinks but no bidet, the fittings are works of art but the overbath shower though powerful does not have a thermostat so watch the hot water tap. An odd omission when so much has been spent on the fittings. Electric towel rail.Good linen and fluffy towels were changed daily.As well as the mini bar also a box of Duchy biscuits and goodies for sale. Free newspaper.Pillows too flat for my taste.Roof terrace fab but not much use in December.Room 314 overlooks the Grand Via, which is 6 lanes of traffic 24hrs a day, when the police pass the junction they blip their sirens yes 24hrs a day. Some poor traffic cop stands for hours at the junction blowing his whistle, it is very entertaining watching his matador like performance. If you need peace and quiet to sleep i suggest you request a quiet room at the back. The view will not match the beautiful view we had as it will overlook a back street .Along the street opposite the restaurant entrance are several restaurants and bars, it looks a bit dark and scruffy but do give them a try. We found the bar half way along on the left good for coffee and pastry in th