<Author>Parkin01
<Content>Great Hotel My boyfriend and I booked at stay at the hotel between 5 and 8 Oct.Unfortunately when we arrived, the hotel advised us that our room had been double booked and we would have to stay in its sister hotel - Bauza for one night. Needless to say, we weren't overly impressed given that I had booked our room nearly three months before. However, the hotel did pay for a taxi to and from the Bauza and the alternative hotel was very nice. Therefore, the only real problem was the inconvenience.When we arrived back at the De Las Letras the next day, the reception staff couldnt have been more helpful and we were advised that we had been upgraded to a room with a roof terrace.The rooms are fantastic - there was a little hallway which leads into the bedroom which was very spacious and the bathroom was a funky red colour with two sinks and an unconventional sliding door! The terrace is a nice touch although we didn't really use it as we were out and about so much.The breakfasts offer a good selection - although it could be set out better as the food is all over the place - including on the window ledges and you have to walk round a few times before you spot everything which is on offer!! And the waiting staff could be a bit more friendly.The bar area is very nice and reasonably priced for a hotel. The terrace bar is also a nice touch - although we didn't actually drink there - but plenty of people seemed to be coming to the hotel specifically to drink there.The only downside to our room was that it was quite noisy. However, the hotel is situated on Gran Via and we had expected this.As others have said, the location of the hotel is fantastic - it is right in the centre of Madrid with everything on the doorstep. We got the Metro from the airport directly to Gran Via station - you have to change twice but its not too much hassle and its so cheap you cant really complain. I would recommend that people buy a 10 trip ticket as it only costs 6 euros and we used it between us.We had several good meals out in Madrid - Finca de Susana near Santa Ana serves good food at cheap prices - but get there when it opens at 8.30 (especially at weekends) or you won't get a table. We also went to Thai Gardens near Serrano which is more expensive but is in a lovely setting for a romantic meal.. Finally I would recommend Lateral for afternoon tapas which is about a 5 minute walk from the hotel.Overall we enjoyed ouy stay at the hotel and would recommend it to others. 
