<Author>dotful
<Content>Trendy and Generally Comfortable in Good Location I stayed in a standard room in this new hotel, and generally agree with most points made by other reviewers. The location is excellent. Definitely at the more attractive end of the sometimes tacky Gran Via, and within easy walking distance of everything you might want to see - from the Prado and Thyssen Bornemisza museums to the trendy Chueca district, smart shopping in the Salamanca area and, in the other direction, the Plaza Mayor (which I'm not mad about) and the Opera/Royal Palace (a nice area, with a great cafe, the Del Oriente).My room was easily spacious enough for one person and good value at 130 Euros,including very good breakfast. They also showed me some superior rooms (not the ones on the top floor), of which the one described as 'triple' would have been well worth upgrading to if I'd come with my husband.  I liked the bathroom (and personally much prefer the delicious smelling French liquid soap to a boring old bar). The bed was lowish but comfortable. I liked the literary extracts (Bunuel in my case) on the walls. I take the point made about no central light but found this no great drawback. The room faced the back, not the Gran Via, and was very quiet.There were just a few things which stop me giving this hotel a complete rave review. I'd asked for a non-smoking room but wasn't given one - obviously I could have asked for a change, but I was very tired and the slight smell of smoke disappeared very quickly. Still,I think a 4-star hotel shouldn't make such basic mistakes. Also, during a cold weekend, there were some problems in getting the heating to operate properly - though the staff were keen to resolve these. And one day there were no toilet rolls in the bathroom - again, speedily put right by the staff, but still ... Lastly, the spa - which I should think is an attractive feature - was out of action. Perhaps these are teething troubles as the hotel is new.I didn't eat in the restaurant at dinner as I like to go out. I did, though, enjoy the drinks and innovative nibbles in the trendy bar, which is very popular with non-residents - including, apparently, the gilded youth of Madrid. This gives it a lively, funky atmosphere, though the cigarette/cigar smoke might put some people off. And because it is so popular I had to wait a while to find a seat and get served. Despite these downsides, I personally preferred it to a conventional,soulless hotel bar.There are good places to eat in easy range - including in Chueca - though (as in many places in Europe) most are closed on Sundays. I asked the reception for recommendations on Sunday evening but they only suggested a pricey tourist-trap type shellfish place near the other, seedier, end of the Gran Via, at which I took one look and moved on. Perhaps it's unreasonable to ask for restaurant recommendations when the hotel has its own, and perhaps the young reception staff, though helpful, are still a little inexperienced.All in all a good, different (though not perfect) base in a great location. 
